<TITLE> Education chiefs gather for regional meet </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Oct 06 (bdnews24.com) More than 100 university presidents and vice-chancellors Monday joined a regional higher education summit in the capital, sponsored by the USAID, to discuss among other issues disaster management and food security. Education Adviser Hossain Zillur Rahman opened the first ever Asia Regional Higher Education Summit, co-hosted by the University of Dhaka and Bangladesh University of Engineering and Technology (BUET). The event is a follow up to the global higher education summit held on April 29-30 in Washington. "It (the Washington summit) aimed at strengthening the role of US and foreign higher education institutions in social and economic development worldwide," James F Moriarty, US ambassador in Dhaka, said in his speech as special guest. USAID's acting assistant administrator (bureau for Asia) Mark Ward, the keynote speaker, said the summit would discuss issues like food security, disaster, teachers' training and women entrepreneurship at the summit. Moderated by USAID's mission director Denise Rollins, the summit was also addressed by Dhaka University VC S M A Faiz, BUET VC A M M Safiullah. Countries that were represented at the summit included Afghanistan, Bangladesh, Cambodia, India, Indonesia, the Kyrgyz Republic, Nepal, Pakistan, the Philippines, Qatar, Sri Lanka, Tajikistan, Thailand, Timor-Leste, the United States and Vietnam. Around 130 university presidents and vice-chancellors, senior executives of businesses and foundations, and government officials from 16 Asian countries are taking part in the three-day conference at Hotel Westi
